.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   )<br>
<br>
I also tend to head towards the 'reasonable man' definition.<br>
<br>
An exploit to me is a unintended aspect of gameplay that a reasonable man would see gives an unfair advantage.<br>
<br>
An exploit that 'breaks the game' is one which reduces the number of strategies for that aspect of the game so much that, ultimately, the exploit is the only worthwhile strategy.<br>
<br>
eg if duping were widespread, there would be no other worthwhile way of making money - indeed other sources would literally be worthless. Nuking from a safe spot or tracking named using SEQ would be less extreme but still serious examples.<br>
<br>
The more unfair the advantage, the more people feel forced to use it, and the more it 'breaks' the game. <br>
Exploits per say are tolerated by SoE; it's only when they approach game breaking that they become serious.<br>
<br>
A complication here is that buffs are *designed* to be an unfair advantage. Someone with a buff is *intended* to have a big advantage over someone without. However it's obvious to me that 3 years ago when Kunark opened, lvl 51+ buffs were not intended to be used on green con players, despite the fact that, objectively, it is a bit arbitrary to have a 49 buff ok on a lvl 1 but a 51 buff not ok on a 33.<br>
<br>
However, many aspects of the game including fd pulling, fear kiting and quad kiting were never intended. Instead of being removed they became 'tolerated exploits' that VI simply chose to make less and less viable as you levelled.<br>
<br>
Whiz, you say that quad kiting got a semi-official endorsement when classes got upgrades to ae snares. You could equally argue that buffing green players was given a semi-official endorsement when SoE added MGB - a full, what, 18 months after the group buff 'exploit' was first created? Not only did they not fix the old Kunark problem, in other words, they made it massively easier and more effective. Now whole zones of newbies could be buffed kei or aego at will. It's hard to believe this aspect went unnoticed especially a year on from luclin now.<br>
<br>
You also argue that quad kiting would be easy to fix simply by making mobs move at a random +/-5% of their snared speed, therefor, again, since no fix has been forthcoming this past 3 years quad kiting is semi-officially endorsed. I'd argue equally that it surely cant be that hard to move the buffing code from checking the target of the spell to checking the recipient. Or an uglier fix would be to allow the group buff to be cast, then simply to check the recipient's buff list once per tick and make any too powerful fade instantly *shrugs*. Again; 3 years of non-fixing is surely as much of an endorsement as quad kiting has ever had, and I assume you have quad kited without qualms.<br>
<br>
So .. why have SoE allowed it to stay with such an agreeably massive effect on low levels? I'd argue that though it was an unintended bug, it had unintended effects that met with new goals that occurred around DAoC (a shift in viewpoint that ultimately caused Brad to leave).<br>
<br>
Certain things were massively complained about about during the first 2 years of EQ's life (during the so called reign of the 'VI vision'). (Not mentioning my views of these complaints) these included:<br>
- overly harsh death penalty &amp; CR, especially for melee who had to run all the way from their town bind point<br>
- forced grouping, esp. indoors for the best loot and xp (though this was first unintentionally changed with the newbie bonus in loio)<br>
- overly slow mana regen<br>
- begging for player ports and binds<br>
- forced spellbook viewing<br>
- buffs not lasting long enough, not enough group buffs, buffs costing too much pp-wise<br>
<br>
Around this time there was also a big reaction to DAoC which promised to be more 'fun' based and eliminate all these alledged frustrating and unnescessary timesinks (again, the complainant's viewpoint not nescessarily my own). SoE feared they would lose a number of their casual minded players, didnt want to give up a single one and so decided to massively broaden their appeal. They wanted to keep their key hard core who they would go on to satisfy with an ever toughening end game, and yet keep happy the 'soft core' who would go on to have almost all gaming frustrations removed.<br>
<br>
- hence the death &amp; CR penalty were largely removed by extra resses, evac's and NPC ports and books (and no CR under 10)<br>
- soloing made increasingly easy for all classes with ever better weapons, armor and potions<br>
- outdoor grouping increasingly made as fast as indoor<br>
- fast mana regen for all (more on this later)<br>
- NPC binding, porting and books<br>
- forced spellbook viewing gone<br>
- buffs doubled or tripled in duration, many more group buffs, one shot raid buffing (MGB), reduced pp cost (eg group virtue half the pp of group aego; force shield, enc rune made componentless etc)<br>
<br>
Lowbies have had a massive boost in regen since kei but so have high levels. Take a look at the difference between a lvl 65 wiz now compared to a lvl 50 wiz pre-kunark (ignoring the manastone nerf):<br>
<br>
+8 - harvest+harvest 2<br>
+8 - druid buff<br>
+8 - flappy<br>
+3 - aa<br>
+10 - improved enc regen<br>
+10 - improved bard regen<br>
+15 - ft (if you're uber)<br>
+20 - horse (if you're outdoors)<br>
+?? - necro &amp; sk boosts<br>
---<br>
80+<br>
<br>
And, you cannot ignore the effect of SCM and MP, because it produces an *effective* mana regen increase of ~15% on top (if it costs less to cast each spell, you regen the mana back quicker so it 'appears' you've had a mana regen increase. With the above level of mana regen SCM3+MP4 produces the same effect as an additional KEI would).<br>
<br>
Now, high level mana increase was largely not done to remove frustrations, it was done much more in the name of balancing melee/caster damage output, and also to balance against casters doubled or tripled manapool.<br>
<br>
I believe it was entirely unintended that kei and aego would affect the low level game as they have - it was a combination of 3 things:<br>
- group buff bug<br>
- 3 hour duration<br>
- serverwide central meeting point (first nexus then pok)<br>
<br>
Lose any of these 3 factors and you'd lose the kei/aego 'effect' on the lower level game.<br>
<br>
But as a final point: SoE doesnt mind the lower level game being imbalanced as long as it is fun for all. In fact fun&gt;all now there, balance only being addressed if it seriously impacts fun. Once you get past 50 they want the game to be increasingly more balanced with much harsher RvR 'old school style' even if it has to come at the expense of fun - eg. allowing classes the 'fun' ability to solo is not in the least a consideration unlike for low levels (though it is still much less harsh than it ever used to be). Hence nearly all the nerfs you see are aimed at balancing the high level game (but occasionally unavoidably nerf the low level game too - eg horses, monk nerf). When was the last purely low level targetted nerf anyone can remember?<br>
<br>
In addition, psychologically people can happily deal with being imbalanced if they know that as they grow levels and gain aa they will become ever more balanced. It's much more frustrating as a gamer to go from a position of being relatively balanced to unbalanced. Hence why the relative importance of fun+balance in the game shift as you grow.<br>
<br>
Stuff us 'hard core' players see as valuable (such as mana management) simply get learnt later than they ever used to (though other stuff like aggro control still has to be learnt). It's a price SoE is prepared to pay to keep their fanbase as broad as it can be and I for one think the balance there pretty good atm <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elasto>Elasto</A> at: 3/31/03 6:29:05 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=izelin>Izelin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 194<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/31/03 7:37:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=56>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> An exploit is something you didnt realize you did, then VI bans you for it.   <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=absolutemaster>Absolute Master</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Channeler</span><br>  Posts: 226<br> <font color=#ffffff>(3/31/03 8:12:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub140.ezboard.com/fgraffeswizardcompilationfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=25564.topic&index=57>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://stuwww.kub.nl/~s338419/everquest/gohan.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Define &quot;exploit&quot;</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Don't call me a noob. I fail to see why you think that your game knoweldge surpasses mine. Calling someone a newbie is a sure fire way to come across as an idiot. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Did I call you a noob? If you believe that SOE intended for newbies to get KEI, then sure go ahead and put yourself in the noob category. They have a level limit on high level buffs for a reason. If SOE intended KEI to be used on low levels, then why would they force you to group with them as the only way to cast on them? You can cast on them due to a bug. Working around a limitation (level limit) by use of this bug is an exploit, it's simple logic. As for the thread, it's in a forum called the Newbie Zone, so a good portion of posters are in fact newbies.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>Oh, you mention that Multiquesting is an exploit. Right. There is an item that can ONLY BE OBTAINED through multiquesting. Why? Because its an ENC/MAG/WIZ item that requires no-drop foraged items. <hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Link to the quest please. If it exists then it is a pretty bad design flaw which needs fixing. Muti-questing IS an exploit. Go ahead and try to get reimbursed on items you handed in as part of a multiquest gone bad. They don't reimburse something they don't approve. You have doubts? Am I making this up? Here's SOE's reimbursement policy in regards to questing.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>12. Quests<br>
<br>
Quests are available in game to gain items and/or experience for performing certain tasks for one or more NPCs.<br>
<br>
   12.1. Items lost in any Quest may be reimbursed after an investigation and at the discretion of a GM.<br>
   <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>12.2. Items that are lost or a reward given to wrong person due to Multi-Questing will not be transferred or reimbursed.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
   12.3. NPCs in Quests that disappear or are killed may not be respawned, nor will items on the NPC's be reimbursed.<br>
   12.4. Items lost in any Quest performed incorrectly may not be reimbursed.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Yup sure sounds as if SOE approves of it. They aren't planning to change the issues (they tend to be rather lazy to fixing bugs which require re-coding of game mechanics), but they make sure to point out that they do not support it.<br>
